</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=straith>Straith</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/8/02 6:08:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=309.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The grey</span><hr size=1> From a Druid perspective in the Grey,<br>
<br>
At 56 I'm oom from quadding the skellies (Need that Lumi staff I guess).  If a rockfiend adds I run it away, root, gate to the SD zone and run back in and find my grouped skellies still standing where they stopped when I gated.<br>
<br>
If you zone in from Scarlet Desert and take a left, there's a good little clearing that I've never seen a mob path to (Unless trained).  Taking a right fromt the zone in will take you to an area that does get some roamers but has even more space.<br>
<br>
The good thing about the mobs, is they run when low on health (if not grouped), which is nice considering they are skeletons.  If you get to be oom with the skellies almost dead, load a low level root and root each one apart from the others and use whatever free damage items you have to finish them off.  If root breaks, they should just stand there while you kill them.<br>
<br>
Fire and Cold spells are partial resists most of the time.  Magic based attacks land very well.<br>
<br>
Wizzies on BB would be welcome to join me, can't beat free Levi/Sow can you?<br>
<br>
On Bristlebane:<br>
Straith 56 Preserver<br>
Straythe 52 Champion<br>
Danrik 51 Illusionist <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=sahhar>Sahhar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/10/02 10:45:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=309.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The grey</span><hr size=1> Helpful stuff here guys and gals. I just began quading in The Grey tonite after getting all these good tips, and all my kiils went smooth, only did 2 quads, but am really excited about this place. Lvl 57 now and never been to excited about raptors. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uquath.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Quath</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/29/02 11:19:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=309.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.pacbell.net/quath/quath.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The grey</span><hr size=1> I live in this zone when I am not raiding.  It still has a fair amount of challenge and with c3, there is not much downtime.  Here are a few more observations about the zone:<br>
<br>
1) You can quad skeletons and snakemen together.  They travel at the same speed.<br>
2) If a worm attacks me, I resnare my quad.  Run a bit and gate to the zone entrance.  I invis and run back.  The last 3 times I have done this, my golems were still standing in a tight bunch motionless.  Wait for worm to depop and finish the kite.<br>
3) If you see a group of quaddable mobs together.  Grab them.  This mostly applies to skeletons.  They are usually lower exp, but killing them is sometimes better than spending a minute or 2 hunting for a 4th golem.<br>
4) The temple camps are nasty.  It is nice from being able to pull 4 mobs as a time, but you have to protect your claim pretty vigilantly.<br>
5) Get a backup EB item for CRs.<br>
6) Some groups dont mind taking your adds.  If you see an exp group near your kite, get to know them.  Some will take my worms and rockfiends for me if I ask.<br>
7) On some pulls, I have to go through snakes and traps to get to one lone golem I see.  So I invis up to walk the mine field.  Grab the golem.  Reinvis and run back.  Adds are the worst enemy of kiting.<br>
8) Familiars are not worth it.  You need to go invis too many times.<br>
9) Trains are bad, m'kay.  Don't do trains.  That being said, just call out your trains.  If you pull anything but rockfiends they will usually stick to you and you can run them over sitting people.  However, a rockfiend has attention deficit disorder and will chase after anyone it sees.  It takes a long run to get distance to cast on a rockfiend.  Sometimes, I stop, turn, cast root, and get that &quot;Target out of range.&quot;  Oops.  Must have trained someone I didn't see.<br>
10) Pulling is an art here.<br>
A) Find areas where you have a wide field of view.<br>
B) When you top a hill and look into a velley.  Pause.  You will see npcs wink in and out of existance.  Watch where they are going.  They may not show up, so prepare for all ghosting issues.  This zone is horrible with this stuff.<br>
C) I have a lot of problems with monster teleportation here.  I will have 3 nicely grouped up and the 4th resisted the snare.  So I will run him by the group, turn and cast it so he is in the group when the snare goes off.  When it works it is great because you just go to nuking.  However, some monsters from the group will teleport to me and start hitting to me.  Thanks Verant.<br>
D) I sometimes solo rockfiends to get them out of my pulling region.  I pull them with snare and solo them.  Pull them at max range.  This gives you a head start to run and root them and then snare them.<br>
<br>
Scott (Quath) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/utorcosiris.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Torc Osiris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/6/02 1:05:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=309.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The grey</span><hr size=1> A great trick if you get more than 4 is to snare 4 (just 4) then zone. <br>
<br>
When you come back the 4 you snared will be standing there, and the others will have gone home. Pull them with a fresh snare and you have a perfect quad waiting for you. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uheliyon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Heliyon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/8/02 1:01:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=309.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The grey</span><hr size=1> Currently doing Shissar Stalkers and revenants (Revenants are a few levels higher than stalkers I suspect) by the temple, and Eternal / Timeless golems (seperately tho, yeah different run speeds).<br>
<br>
Without KEI, I usually end up with about 30% of my mana free on the golems, and 1 cast of PoLightning away from OOM with shissars.<br>
<br>
Shissars are of higher level than golems, and thus yeild a tad more exp per quad, or at least by my subjective observations ;p<br>
<br>
I like the grey, nice and uncamped, pretty quiet, not too many druids ninja pulling my stuffs, and necros are usually willing to take my rock fiends (hello hides $ ) .<br>
